havior at start. In initial testing a starting speed of 20 and then gradual ramp up to 3,4,5... max produced a smooth acceleration that takes a little less than a second.</comment><value name="VALUE"><shadow type="math_number" id="|vug`$*3EveRiA,DUlrF"><field name="NUM">0</field></shadow><block type="variables_get" id="P_FN%B%*]Gdgv2lZ8h9n"><field name="VAR" id="KJ;N;|]wq5GSbCz~h,5x">normal_start_speed</field></block></value></block></next></block></next></block></statement><statement name="ELSE"><block type="quest_Note_1_quest_Show_String_For_Note_Small_Func" id="8oKFjDo6E2QuUfaPmu@J"><value name="textStrIn"><shadow type="text" id="q2_4+w+fpP)Sx4Bvu]I1"><field name="TEXT">user is holding stick forward - accelerate and hold</field></shadow></value><next><block type="quest_Note_1_quest_Show_String_For_Note_Small_Func" id="a#@_%b?PQ#UNm(]LK+[%"><comment pinned="false" h="80" w="160">smooth accel begins at normal_start_speed and ends at the value specified below by (max_normal_speed/n).
For smooth acceleration to Max normal speed make the divisor (n) equal to one.
